Bushfires in Queensland and flooding rains in Sydney have raised online debate
in Australia about the impact of climate change on extreme weather conditions.

On Wednesday, 28 November 2018, record temperatures in central Queensland
resulted in 200 fires, which some classified as
[catastrophic](https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-11-28/queensland-bushfires-
gracemere-deepwater-rules-beach-baffle-blog/10561514). Eight thousand people
were evacuated from the town of Gracemere just near the regional center of
Rockhampton.

Further south, a monthâ€™s rainfall
[inundated](https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-11-28/sydney-weather-storms-
disrupt-roads-and-morning-commute/10560198) Sydney on the same day, with 100
millimetres (4 inches) recorded in just two hours. There was widespread
flooding and property damage, as well as two reported deaths. One â€˜mini-
cycloneâ€™ tore off the side of a building.

